  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, many countries have specific laws and regulations targeting money laundering. In the United States, key anti-money laundering (AML) laws include the Bank Secrecy Act and the USA PATRIOT Act. These laws require financial institutions to:\n\n1. Report large cash transactions\n2. Implement customer identification programs\n3. Monitor and report suspicious financial activities\n4. Maintain records of financial transactions\n\nInternationally, organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Most developed countries have similar legal frameworks to detect and prevent money laundering.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
